 <p>In a <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/q/79743788/8447743">previous question</a> I asked for a way to send async workloads between threads and got the following, working answer from @ChrisB:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub struct Context(i32); // example

pub enum InnerAsyncEvent {
    DoWithContext {
        block: Box&lt;
            dyn for&lt;'a&gt; Fn(
                &amp;'a mut Context
            ) -&gt; Pin&lt;Box&lt;dyn Future&lt;Output = ()&gt; + Send + 'a&gt;&gt;
            + Send,
        &gt;,
    },
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let event = InnerAsyncEvent::DoWithContext {
        block: Box::new(|ctx: &amp;mut Context| {
            Box::pin(async move { ctx.0 += 1 })
        }),
    };

    tokio::spawn(async {
        let mut ctx = Context(0);
        let fut = match event {
            InnerAsyncEvent::DoWithContext { block } =&gt; block(&amp;mut ctx),
        };
        fut.await;
    });
}
</code></pre>
<p>This is nice, but I find the construction of the async workload rather complicated. I'd much rather just pass a symple async closure and the have that appropriately pinned by a utility, if that makes sense. Would that be possible? I'm hoping to make something along the lines of the following work:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>pub fn with_context_async(&amp;mut work_sender: Sender&lt;InnerAsyncEvent&gt;, block: impl for&lt;'a&gt; AsyncFnOnce(
            &amp;'a mut Context
        ) + Send + 'static) {

    let _ = work_sender.send(InnerAsyncEvent::DoWithContext {
        block: Box::new(|ctx| Box::pin(async move { block(ctx).await })),
    });
}
</code></pre>
<p>however, this errors with</p>
<blockquote>
<p>future cannot be sent between threads safely
within <code>{async block@blabla.rs:1160:46: 1160:56}</code>, the trait <code>std::marker::Send</code> is not implemented for <code>&lt;... as AsyncFnOnce&lt;...&gt;&gt;::CallOnceFuture</code>
required for the cast from <code>Pin&lt;Box&lt;{async block@blabla:1160:46: 1160:56}&gt;&gt;</code> to <code>Pin&lt;Box&lt;dyn futures::Future&lt;Output = ()&gt; + std::marker::Send&gt;&gt;</code></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Can this be made to work on stable Rust?</p>


